definition.value: An amino cyclitol that is scyllo-inositol in which the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 are replaced by guanidino groups.
A linolenic acid with cis-double bonds at positions 9, 12 and 15. Shown to have an antithrombotic effect.
A pyrimidone obtained by formal addition of hydrogen across the 5,6-position of thymine.

An N-acyl-amino acid that is a form of the water-soluble vitamin B9. Its biologically active forms (tetrahydrofolate and others) are essential for nucleotide biosynthesis and homocysteine remethylation.
A pyrimidine that is a derivative of cytosine, having a methyl group at the 5-position.
A  saturated organic heteromonocyclic parent that is a three-membered heterocycle of two carbon atoms and one oxygen atom.
An aminobenzoic acid that is salicylic acid substituted by an amino group at position 4.
An alpha-amino acid that is propanoic acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2 and a 1H-imidazol-4-yl group at position 3.

A pregnane-based steroidal hormone produced by the outer-section (zona glomerulosa) of the adrenal cortex in the adrenal gland, and acts on the distal tubules and collecting ducts of the kidney to cause the conservation of sodium, secretion of potassium, increased water retention, and increased blood pressure. The overall effect of aldosterone is to increase reabsorption of ions and water in the kidney.

A nine-membered bis-lactone having methyl substituents at the 2- and 6-positions, an n-hexyl substituent at the 8-position, an acyloxy substituent at the 7-position and an aroylamido substituent at the 3-position. It is produced by Streptomyces bacteria and has found commercial use as a fish poison.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of vanillylmandelic acid.
A cobalt group element atom that has atomic number 27.

A dicarboximide that is 4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperidine-2,6-dione in which one of the hydrogens attached to the carbon  bearing the hydroxy group is replaced by a 3,5-dimethyl-2-oxocyclohexyl group. It is an antibiotic produced by the bacterium Streptomyces griseus.
A member of the class of tetracyclines with formula C22H23ClN2O8 isolated from Streptomyces aureofaciens.

A pyranoindolizinoquinoline that is pyrano[3',4':6,7]indolizino[1,2-b]quinoline which is substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 14, and by an ethyl group and a hydroxy group at position 4 (the S enantiomer).
Any aldehyde having an oxo substituent at the 2-position.
A D-galactopyranose having beta configuration at the anomeric centre.
A fatty acid anion 10:0 that is the conjugate base of decanoic acid.
A member of the class of phytosterols that is stigmast-5-ene substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.

A tetracycline used for treatment of infections caused by a variety of Gram positive and Gram negative microorganisms including Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Pasteurella pestis, Escherichia coli, Haemophilus influenzae (respiratory infections), and Diplococcus pneumoniae.
A trimethylxanthine in which the three methyl groups are located at positions 1, 3, and 7. A purine alkaloid that occurs naturally in tea and coffee.
A surfactant (or a mixture containing one or more surfactants) having cleaning properties in dilute solutions.
A member of the class of benzimidazoles that is benzimidazole in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by an amino group.
A member of the class of indole-3-acetic acids that is  indole-3-acetic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at C-5.
A stilbenol that is stilbene in which the phenyl groups are substituted at positions 3, 5, and 4' by hydroxy groups.
An S-substituted L-cysteine where the S-substituent is specified as a sulfo group.
An alpha-amino acid that is alanine bearing an indol-3-yl substituent at position 3.
A broad-spectrum polyketide antibiotic produced by the Streptomyces genus of actinobacteria.
An organonitrogen heterocyclic antibiotic that contains a beta-lactam ring.
An amino cyclitol consisting of scyllo-inositol with the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 replaced by unsubstituted amino groups.
A tropane alkaloid obtained from leaves of the South American shrub Erythroxylon coca.
A 9-octadecenoic acid and the trans-isomer of oleic acid.

A complex glycopeptide from Streptomyces orientalis. It inhibits a specific step in the synthesis of the peptidoglycan layer in the Gram-positive bacteria Staphylococcus aureus and Clostridium difficile.
An aromatic amino acid that is alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a phenyl group.
A histidine derivative that is histidine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the alpha-amino group has been replaced by a 4-aminobutanoyl group.
D-Galactopyranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A member of the class of rifamycins that is a a semisynthetic antibiotic derived from Amycolatopsis rifamycinica (previously known as Amycolatopsis mediterranei and Streptomyces mediterranei).
